You are in the Town Square.
You can see Glühwein and a Choir Leader.

You can go west, north, east, southeast or south.
As the name suggests it's a square in the town, and as it's christmas there is a German market including a Glühwein stall .

There are also some carol singers, they are currently belting out a hearty rendition of Stay Another Day by East 17 to a disinterested crowd of busy shoppers who scurry by.

> x gluhwein

> x gluhwein

Hot steaming Glühwein, in a plastic cup
> take it

> take it

You pick it up.
> drink it

> drink it

You peer into the Glühwein, it a deep red, hot and steamy, you could do with the Dutch courage to deal with the crowds so you down it in one...its rather too hot and stings your throat and it tastes like hot vimto. Unfortunately all the alcohol seems to have been boiled off, probably sometime in early December
> x cup

> x cup

A transparent empty plastic cup that smells of Glühwein
> x leader

> x leader

A tall man with a bushy black beard speckled with grey, wearing wire-frame glasses, a smart Dickensian style suit, greatcoat and sporting a caroler top hat. He's singing his heart out with the rest of the choir, but he's scanning the square and is obviously disappointed at the lack of interest from the crowds wandering past.
> x singers

> x singers

A mixed group of young and old carol singers, dressed in warm coats, hats and scarfs; which is just as well as the temperature seems to be dropping.
> sing

> sing

You sing, the carol singers increase in volume, the crowd starts singing. For a moment the whole town square is united in a joyous brief pause from the commercial hustle and bustle.

The carol leader walks over and shakes your hand, "here take this,". He hands you a Bottle of Port
> x port

> x port

It's a bottle of Taylor's Late Bottled Vintage Port 2010, very nice!
> n

> n

You are in Santa's Christmas Emporium.
You can see Santa, a Sprig of Holly, a Scarf and a teddy.

You can go south, down or east.

a shop specialising in christmas toys and decorations, it looks like its been ransacked by the shoppers, most of the shelves are bare with the odd bauble, tinsel and teddy bear scattered about the place

> x holly

> x holly

A small twig of holly with three spiky leaves and a cluster of dark red berries
> x scarf

> x scarf

It is a small scarf, probably made for a child. It is a faded blue colour with a repeated pattern of a snowman with an orange for a nose, wearing a floppy green hat and a green scarf.
> x teddy

> x teddy

Nothing out of the ordinary.
> take scarf

> take scarf

You pick it up.
> x Santa

> x Santa

A portly, smiling, white-bearded man with half-moon spectacles, and a twinkle in his eye. He's wearing a red coat with white collar and cuffs, white-cuffed red trousers, and black leather belt and boots. He's sat on a large leather armchair.
> talk to Santa

> talk to Santa

Greetings! And a Merry Christmas to you! Ho Ho Ho etc. How can I help you?
> sit on Santa

> sit on Santa

You sit down on Santa's knee. Santa says "What would like for Christmas?" You whisper in his ear. Santa chuckles and says "Well, you've been good this year, here you go" He hands you a parcel and a card." You say "thank you" and stand up
> i

> i

You are carrying a Shopping List, a Carrot, an Empty Plastic Cup, a Bottle of Port, a Scarf, a Present From Santa and a Christmas Card.
> x present

> x present

A rectangular parcel wrapped in red paper with green ribbon tied in a bow.
> x card

> x card

A cheap Christmas card, printed on thin card. It has a clichéd depiction of a nativity scene on the front. Inside it says 'Seasons Greetings!' in a poorly chosen font, but underneath in perfect handwritten copperplate script it reads “Merry Christmas, you’ve been good this year! All the best from Santa and Rudolph xxx PS: Sorry about the cheap card, terrible supply problems this year.”
> ask Santa about Rudolph

> ask Santa about Rudolph

"How else would I light my merry way? Especially when it's foggy."
> open present

> open present

You're tempted to open the present, but you decide to be good and save it for tomorrow
> d

> d

You are in an Elves Workshop.
You can see a Chief Elf.

You can go up.
You are in the Elves Workshop, there are row upon row of workbenches with toys, decorations and christmas paraphernalia of every type in various states of completion.On the wall is a poster.

There is a gang of Elves here

> x chief

> x chief

You can see why this guy is the 'Chief' Elf, he's taller than you! His lanky frame is all arms and legs, he's wearing a green robe trimmed with white fur, a green and yellow striped cone-shaped hat and yellow stockings.

He has a face as long as a fortnight, one unhappy chap.
> x gang

> x gang

The elves are sat playing cards, they look bored.
> x poster

> x poster

The poster reads, "Christmas Cracker joke writer wanted, excellent rates of pay, enquire with Chief Elf"
> take poster

> take poster

You pick it up.
> talk to chief

> talk to chief

The Chief Elf looks at you witheringly, "and what do YOU want?" he says.
> ask chief about poster

> ask chief about poster

Why don't you try reading it!
> ask chief about writer

> ask chief about writer

"Yes we're after a new one, the old one was far too witty"
> ask chief about Santa

> ask chief about Santa

"Don't get me wrong I love the guy, would do anything for him, but his demands are relentless."
> ask chief about elves

> ask chief about elves

I love my boys, hardest grafters you've ever seen!
> ask chief about toys

> ask chief about toys

Toys? My boys make the best! But not today, I'm sick of being taken for granted around here, haven't had a pay rise for years, no overtime even on Christmas Eve...come the revolution.." he continues to grumpily reel off a list of complaints and empty revolutionary slogans
