You are on a Tib Street.
You can see a Bench.

You can go west or east.
You are on a small quiet side street off the town square, running from west to east. In the distance you can hear the singing in the town square.

> x bench

> x bench

A Victorian public bench made from cast iron and wooden slats.
> sit on bench

> sit on bench

You sit down to rest on the bench, after a few seconds you hear a ringing emanating from the bench, looking down you see a mobile phone lodged between the wooden slates of the bench.

You pick it up.

> x phone

> x phone

A black smart phone, it's some generic cheap brand that you don't recognise. On the lock screen you can see 7 missed calls from 'Marley'.
> e

> e

You are in a Stable.
You can see a Reindeer.

You can go south or west.
There is clean straw on the floor, a food trough and behind that stands a Reindeer. The Reindeer snorts gently as you enter.

> x reindeer

> x reindeer

It's a reindeer, thick soft mottled brown fur, furry antlers, and yes of course a bright red nose. He seems friendly and wanders over for you to stroke him, you notice that he is limping slightly
> x foot

> x foot

it's a reindeer hoof, cloven with two toes at the front and one at the back
It contains a nail.
> x nail

> x nail

a 4 inch nail, bent slightly at the pointy end
> take nail

> take nail

You examine the reindeer's hoof and find a nail stuck in it. You remove it. The reindeer nuzzles you in thanks
> x straw

> x straw

Clean straw, looks like the stable has recently been cleaned out and refreshed
> x trough

> x trough

A food trough or manger, full of oats
> x oats

> x oats

Just dry oats, nothing special
> stroke reindeer

> stroke reindeer

You stroke the Reindeer, it nuzzles against you in a ridiculously endearing manner
> give carrot to reindeer

> give carrot to reindeer

You give the carrot to the Reindeer, who munches it down. A few seconds later it grunts and deposits a small gift of some fresh Reindeer dung
> x dung

> x dung

a small mound of berry sized brown droppings, slightly steaming
> take dung

> take dung

You scoop up the dung with the empty plastic cup
> s

> s

You are in The Cross Keys Inn.
You can see a Jukebox, a Pool Table and a Fruit Machine.

You can go west or north.
A great British pub, just like they used to be, all sticky carpets and wet tables. Thanks to the smoking ban there is a persistent scent of stale spilt beer and urinals.

Propping up the bar is a rake thin man in his late 30's, hunkered in an unkempt and crumpled raincoat, he has a mop of ginger hair and is nursing an advocaat and lemonade.

You've got a lot to do today, but there is always time for a pint, and you've got a thirst on!

> buy beer

> buy beer

The Rake Thin Man says, "If you're after a drink then The Landlady is out the back somewhere, probably asleep"
> x man

> x man

Thin, haggard and world beaten, but with young eyes. He stares into his drink as if its a portal to a lost world. Next to him on the bar is a string bag of satsumas. Periodically he checks the weather app on his phone. He gives off a faint air of fried chicken.
> talk to man

> talk to man

"Hello" says the Rake Thin Man and gives you a half smile
> x satsumas

> x satsumas

a handful of satsumas in an orange string bag, they smell ripe and zesty
> ask man about satsumas

> ask man about satsumas

"Oh these, just in case I need a nose, but the weather is looking too dry tonight"
> ask man about weather

> ask man about weather

"Only a 5% chance of snow tonight, damn climate change"
> give scarf to man

> give scarf to man

The man's face lights up in a childlike grin, "my scarf! I thought it was lost forever!" How can I possibly repay you?

You nod hopefully at the bag of satsumas on the bar. "Oh those, well it looks like its not going to snow yet again this xmas eve"

He looks wistfully away. "Here take them, the name's James by the way". He shakes you by the hand.
> x jukebox

> x jukebox

A jukebox and it's a nice one, a genuine Wurlitzer with actual vinyl singles inside. A label next to the coin slot reads "Insert coin to play'
> x table

> x table

A traditional pub pool table, 7 x 4 foot. The green baize is in decent enough condition, and there are only a few drink stains, but all the balls are accumulated at one corner. It leans so much it's unplayable.
> x machine

> x machine

An Only Fools and Horses themed Fruit Machine, with three reels. It looks like someone has left 1 credit on it.
> play machine

> play machine

You press the 'Start button', the three reels spin and thump to stop one at a time...
Cherry.......Cherry.....and.......Cherry!
The machine makes an over dramatic electronic 'whoop whoop' noise and plays a snippet of the Only Fools and Horses theme music. You hit the collect button, the machine makes a satisfying Ker-Chunk noise and deposits a pound coin in the bottom tray. You place the coin in your pocket
> x coin

> x coin

A pound coin, Queen's head on one side, and a Thistle and Royal Diadem on the other. Inscribed around the edge it reads "NEMO ME IMPUNE LACESSIT"
> turn on jukebox

> turn on jukebox

You insert the pound coin into the jukebox, a record swings down on to the platter with a satisfying soft clunk. The opening bars of War Is Over (if you want it) play warmly through the room, as if by magic the Landlady appears
> x landlady

> x landlady

The Landlady has finally appeared, and has clearly just woken up. What she lacks in stature she makes up for in steely presence and inscrutable countenance.
> talk to landlady

> talk to landlady

"Welcome" says the Landlady, "what can I get you?"
> buy beer

> buy beer

The landlady says, "I don't give away beer for free, perhaps you make yourself useful around here and I'll reconsider"
> ask landlady about pool table

> ask landlady about pool table

Damn thing's wonky as a hell, used to get loads of people in here playing on it.
> fold card

> fold card

You fold the card in half
> use card on table

> use card on table

You place the folded christmas card under the leg in the corner of the table where the balls keep accumulating.  The balls roll back to the centre. You've fixed it!
> buy beer

> buy beer

"Here you go love, thanks for fixing the table, might actually get a few more customers in here now"
> x beer

> x beer

A pint of 'Good Elf' Christmas Ale, it's a dark umber colour with a creamy looking head. It smells of sultanas and liquorice.
